WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.920
Hi, everyone. My name is Gordon Shotwell. I'm a data scientist at a company called Socure.

00:00:06.920 --> 00:00:12.640
We do fraud prevention. And I'm going to talk to you about Quarto and Jupyter. How many

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:21.360
of you are Jupyter users? Yeah? Okay. So, this is a website. You can follow at Quarto.Shotwell.ca

00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:28.920
if you are interested. So, I, a lot of my work is running a shared data science server.

00:00:28.920 --> 00:00:32.720
And Socure has grown like crazy over the last three years. So, it's been, it went from

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:40.080
something like 20 users to more like 100. And it's kind of like ballpark the editors

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:44.400
that people use on the server. So, a lot of Jupyter users, some VS Code people, and some

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:50.520
RStudio people. What I noticed is that all of my headaches come from the Jupyter users.

00:00:50.520 --> 00:00:54.919
Every time there's a problem, every time something breaks or something can't be launched, I just

00:00:54.919 --> 00:01:01.240
say Jupyter. And I started asking, like, why is this? Why does this editor cause me

00:01:01.240 --> 00:01:06.959
personally so many problems? Not that I use it. I'm not a Jupyter user. But other people

00:01:06.959 --> 00:01:14.760
break my server using this tool. And I think the key problem is that Jupyter uses like

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:21.160
a fundamentally different development pattern than other computer science tools. And this

00:01:21.160 --> 00:01:24.800
causes a lot of problems when you try to integrate it with any of these other computer

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:29.480
science tools. A lot of the tooling around programming is built around a different paradigm

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:36.680
than Jupyter. And the way I put this is that they differentiate between the editorial environment

00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:41.080
and the execution environment. There's usually a clear, bright line between the times when

00:01:41.080 --> 00:01:44.919
you're editing something and the times when you're running something. But Jupyter blends

00:01:44.919 --> 00:01:48.599
those two together. And that's really part of the design of the software. It's supposed

00:01:48.599 --> 00:01:54.559
to be an interactive notebook environment that lets you play with your data and move

00:01:54.559 --> 00:02:01.919
back and forth. But it causes a lot of problems. So, some of these problems are because you're

00:02:01.919 --> 00:02:08.300
kind of like the user is also executing the data, they might do that kind of out of order.

00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:14.240
And that state can become very complex. It can become difficult to reason about or record.

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:19.639
The code itself can cause sort of deep, profound problems to your editor. So, you might run

00:02:19.639 --> 00:02:25.240
something weird, do some sort of odd memory thing. And then suddenly, like, just Jupyter

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:29.279
doesn't work for a long time. And you don't know why. It's very hard to figure out. It's

00:02:29.279 --> 00:02:34.039
not just like something crashing, but something kind of deeper happening to the software.

00:02:34.039 --> 00:02:39.000
And then integrations of other computer systems can be difficult. In particular, Git can be

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:44.000
difficult. So, this is the kind of JSON that a Jupyter notebook is stored. So, when you

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:50.919
just naively try to check in a Jupyter notebook to Git, you try to use any of the systems

00:02:50.919 --> 00:02:55.240
that kind of rely on Git as GitHub or something as an input, you kind of end up with this

00:02:55.240 --> 00:03:00.919
thing. And this is really easy to make mistakes with. So, you can, for instance, check credentials

00:03:00.919 --> 00:03:06.520
into your Git repository. You can check in PII that's not supposed to be in a Git repository.

00:03:06.520 --> 00:03:11.399
Just because it's this giant, unreadable JSON blob. It's very difficult to review.

00:03:11.399 --> 00:03:16.199
So, recently I came across this wonderful blog post about how the Jupyter Git problem

00:03:16.199 --> 00:03:20.520
has been solved. And the thing that I kind of was thinking about when I was looking at

00:03:20.520 --> 00:03:24.399
this is that it just shouldn't take this long, right? It shouldn't... Git is a basic sort

00:03:24.399 --> 00:03:28.479
of thing that's existed for a long time. It works with almost everything. Like, it shouldn't

00:03:28.479 --> 00:03:33.119
take, you know, like, millions of dollars and ten years of dedicated work to get the

00:03:33.119 --> 00:03:42.479
system to function on Git. So, the way I'd sort of put this is that, like, to kind of

00:03:42.479 --> 00:03:47.279
like break it out a little bit, put a little graph on it, most programs use this kind of

00:03:47.279 --> 00:03:51.360
like write-execute model. So, you have, you know, you're writing your code, and then you

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:56.440
have this source code, which is kind of like a rigid... It determines what the outputs

00:03:56.440 --> 00:03:59.919
are gonna be, right? So, this is kind of like executor. It goes and reads this source code,

00:03:59.919 --> 00:04:04.479
sources it, and then produces some outputs. This creates a lot of wonderful things because

00:04:04.479 --> 00:04:09.960
this actually is a useful data structure. It's a thing you can sort of track over time.

00:04:09.960 --> 00:04:15.600
It's something you can analyze to do static code analysis or something like that. And

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:19.440
this executor is kind of like always does the same thing. Like, there's no humans in

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:23.359
this part. So, you kind of have confidence that once you know what's happening here,

00:04:23.359 --> 00:04:27.480
you know what's gonna happen here in the outputs.

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:33.160
But Jupyter uses what I would call kind of like a re-execute model. You write the code,

00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:39.200
and then that kind of creates this sort of like code output construct. And then when

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:43.799
you're kind of like running the code or working through it, that's actually modifying the

00:04:43.799 --> 00:04:49.359
sort of code output structure. And there's ways that you can sort of like parse the code

00:04:49.359 --> 00:04:53.359
out of that. There's ways you can kind of parse the code out of it. But the tool itself

00:04:53.359 --> 00:04:59.519
kind of pushes users to have this kind of like highly unsteady interactive workflow.

00:04:59.519 --> 00:05:03.160
And I think that's one of the things I've observed about people who are very, very skilled

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:08.640
and excellent data scientists. But because they kind of maybe learned to do this as the

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:13.320
way that they work, they kind of have a little bit of a moat around moving to sort of like

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:21.160
more general computer science workflows. So, R actually had a different whole pattern to

00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:27.040
notebook development, which is these write-execute notebooks. So, when you write an R Markdown

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:34.279
notebook, this is RMD style, you actually just write the sort of code and text together

00:05:34.279 --> 00:05:39.320
in a single document. And just like source code, that document is kind of a rigid artifact.

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:44.959
It's just text. There's no logic in the R Markdown notebook. There's no state in the

00:05:44.959 --> 00:05:52.600
R Markdown notebook. It's just text. And what the renderer does is take that document,

00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:57.239
go find all the things that are labeled as code, pass that code through an interpreter,

00:05:57.239 --> 00:06:03.679
and then put the code and the text back together into these output formats. And this is a really

00:06:03.679 --> 00:06:13.160
wonderful pattern, because like most of the things work right away, right? So, there hasn't

00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:18.239
ever been like an R Markdown Git parser, right? Because R Markdown documents are just text,

00:06:18.239 --> 00:06:23.880
so they just work with Git, right? It's just like any other computer source code from when

00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:27.839
there were punch cards, right? It's a text that's then interpreted. Similarly, if you

00:06:27.839 --> 00:06:33.440
ever use like NuMake or any of those orchestration tools, they work really well with this code,

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:38.279
because that's kind of what they're expecting. They're expecting text that's then run through

00:06:38.279 --> 00:06:42.200
some kind of interpreter. Similarly, it's really, really easy to compose R Markdown

00:06:42.239 --> 00:06:46.119
notebooks. You could either copy and paste them together or parse them together in some

00:06:46.119 --> 00:06:51.720
other format. It's easy to package libraries, and it's also really easy to mix languages. So,

00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:56.399
you can, I think, use something like 17 different computer programming languages in an R Markdown

00:06:56.399 --> 00:07:00.000
document, and they'll all play well together, because it just goes and finds the Python code,

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.640
runs it through a Python interpreter, goes and finds the Scala code, runs it through a Scala

00:07:03.640 --> 00:07:10.320
interpreter, right? And these are all kind of well-solved problems in computer science.

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:14.640
But there's three big problems. The first problem is that it starts with the letter R,

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:20.519
right? And so, I work with a lot of Python users, and, you know, it's just, it's their

00:07:20.519 --> 00:07:25.720
least favourite letter. If you propose any kind of tool or solution, and that solution starts with

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:34.079
R, or even has an R in it, they just say no. The second sort of maybe more real problem is that it

00:07:34.079 --> 00:07:39.399
requires an R runtime, right? So, R is a very niche programming language. It's not sort of

00:07:39.399 --> 00:07:42.799
necessarily installed on everybody's laptop. You know, it's not installed on every server,

00:07:42.799 --> 00:07:49.119
so that can be difficult. And the last one is that it has a slightly inconsistent user interface.

00:07:49.119 --> 00:07:54.160
So, R Markdown is a ten-year-old technology, and over time, it's kind of been elaborated on to do

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:59.519
a lot of different things. So, like, people write their blogs in it, or my blog in R Markdown. This,

00:07:59.519 --> 00:08:04.160
you know, you could write presentations in R Markdown, books, you know, and then also just

00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:07.480
kind of data science reports. And over time, it's accommodated all of those use cases,

00:08:07.720 --> 00:08:12.160
kind of started adding different options, and those options started drifting in terms of how

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:18.640
consistent they were. So, this is where Cordo comes in. Cordo is a new project from RStudio,

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:26.720
and the main feature of it is that it's a fully language-agnostic version of R Markdown. So,

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:32.640
it's a TypeScript command line utility. It doesn't have any R or Python dependency. You can use it

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:39.599
for just R, you can use it for R and Python, or Observable, or JavaScript, or Julia. It also has

00:08:39.599 --> 00:08:46.000
a lot better branding, just because, speaking personally, I've had at work many, many times

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:50.320
where I've just seen people waste, like, huge amounts of money on things that really could

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:55.200
have been a scheduled R Markdown document, right? And I have not been able to convince a single one

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:59.320
of them to use a scheduled R Markdown document to solve their problem. But every one of them,

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:03.640
as soon as I talk about Cordo, they're really excited about Cordo, because the capabilities

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:07.960
that it has and how simple it is are really powerful. But it doesn't start with the letter

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:14.640
R, so it kind of, like, gets through the gate. And then, lastly, it's got a unified extensible

00:09:14.640 --> 00:09:20.200
interface. So, it's kind of, the interface is focused a little bit more on Pandoc, which I'll

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:25.280
get to in a second. And so, that means that it kind of, like, it's a lot more consistent and

00:09:25.280 --> 00:09:32.559
easier to work with. So, how does this work? So, you write a QMD document, which looks a lot

00:09:32.559 --> 00:09:36.080
like an RMD document, if you've ever been familiar with, if you're familiar with that. So, it's

00:09:36.080 --> 00:09:41.840
Markdown with sort of specific code chunks. And then, when you render that document, Cordo goes

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:47.599
and does, passes the code through an executor, or through an interpreter, and then puts together

00:09:47.599 --> 00:09:54.159
this Markdown document, which is, so, the output of the code is turned into Markdown, and the text

00:09:54.640 --> 00:10:00.559
is put where the text goes, just as Markdown. And this goes to a system called Pandoc, and Pandoc

00:10:00.559 --> 00:10:09.280
is this really incredible tool for turning documents into other documents. So, it has,

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:14.880
basically, what's called, like, an abstract syntax tree on top of documents. So, it says, like, you

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:20.559
know, for a PDF, this part of a PDF kind of maps on to this abstract syntax tree, which then maps

00:10:20.559 --> 00:10:25.119
down to a Word document, or a PowerPoint document, or something like that. So, with Pandoc, you can

00:10:25.119 --> 00:10:29.679
take this Markdown file and render it into, you know, lots and lots and lots of different formats.

00:10:29.679 --> 00:10:36.719
So, this slideshow is done that way. You can do HTML, of course, websites, books, all these types

00:10:36.719 --> 00:10:43.440
of different things. This is what the code format looks like, if you're totally unfamiliar with it.

00:10:43.440 --> 00:10:48.799
So, this is just something you can write in a text editor. And, basically, the sort of two

00:10:48.799 --> 00:10:53.520
things. So, most of this is Markdown notation. So, those are, like, headings. And then you have

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:58.159
these little backticks that define, like, inline code. So, this would be, like, an inline code

00:10:58.159 --> 00:11:03.599
chunk. And then you could have code chunks that sort of specify the language here, and then you

00:11:03.599 --> 00:11:08.400
can just run code. So, what Cordo does is it goes and it finds anything like this, passes it through

00:11:08.400 --> 00:11:13.840
the interpreter that's labeled by this thing, and then produces the output. So, in this case, that

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:17.760
would produce an output that looks like this, right? Does the calculation of the two, puts

00:11:17.760 --> 00:11:27.919
out the text. It's like that. So, the main sort of advantages of this is that it moves you from

00:11:27.919 --> 00:11:32.719
this kind of, like, fuzzy place where you're not really sure what your source code is. Like, is it

00:11:32.719 --> 00:11:36.799
the sort of document you've produced, or is it the one where you produced and then ran some chunks?

00:11:36.799 --> 00:11:41.840
Instead, you have this sort of clear idea of, like, the QMD file that you're working with.

00:11:41.840 --> 00:11:45.760
That's the source code, right? So, that's the thing that you can check into Git. You can share

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:52.799
with people. You can test more easily. You can analyze more easily. It gives you all the benefits

00:11:52.799 --> 00:11:59.520
of Pandoc. So, you can render really beautiful sort of full-featured PDFs. You know, there's

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:04.239
lots of different academic journal formats, things like that. Great caching, and you can compose

00:12:04.239 --> 00:12:07.679
notebooks together. So, you can have lots of notebooks together that make a website. If you

00:12:07.679 --> 00:12:13.119
want to look at a website like that, you can look at my website. But you don't actually need to

00:12:13.119 --> 00:12:18.880
abandon Jupyter to start using this. So, you can still use Jupyter as your main editorial

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:26.880
environment, because Cordo can render Jupyter notebooks without altercation and preview them.

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:31.919
And then you can also convert really easily back and forth between a Jupyter format and a Cordo

00:12:31.919 --> 00:12:38.719
format. So, you kind of don't need to actually change much about your work. And then one thing

00:12:38.719 --> 00:12:47.599
that I would recommend is this NBDev, which is by Jeremy Coward, who does fast AI. He kind of

00:12:47.599 --> 00:12:57.039
uses Cordo as basically the publication layer on top of that kind of notebook development pattern.

00:12:57.039 --> 00:13:03.599
So, the way to get started, you can go to Cordo.org. It's also included with the latest release of

00:13:03.599 --> 00:13:09.119
RStudio. So, you don't need to install anything. The RStudio visual editor is really wonderful,

00:13:09.119 --> 00:13:15.359
whether or not you're an R user. It's a really great visual markdown editor, which kind of lets

00:13:15.359 --> 00:13:19.359
you sort of use these things really well. There's a VS code extension that's also really good.

00:13:20.559 --> 00:13:27.919
And so, the main sort of rules here is that what you should try to do is store the code asset as

00:13:27.919 --> 00:13:32.880
a QMD document. So, that's something where it's like, if you're working with Jupyter notebooks,

00:13:32.880 --> 00:13:38.000
great, work with it. And then you want to at some point write and check in this text file

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:43.919
that's just the document in the report. And when you share it, you should share it with that thing

00:13:43.919 --> 00:13:48.799
and then probably some kind of environment definition, like if you use Conda or Virtualenv

00:13:48.799 --> 00:13:53.919
or something like that. And the thing that you share with people who want to read the code,

00:13:53.919 --> 00:13:57.520
who aren't going to go execute and work on the code, but just want to read the report,

00:13:57.520 --> 00:14:01.679
is the render document, which can include both the code that you used to do it as well as the

00:14:02.320 --> 00:14:07.039
prettily formatted output. Yeah, and that's what I've got.

